{{Infobox ethnic group |group=Chinese people in Namibia |population=various estimates |popplace=[[Windhoek]]{{·}}[[Oshakati]]<ref name="Xoagub"/> |langs=[[Chinese language|Chinese]]{{·}}[[English language|English]] }}
The number of '''Chinese people in Namibia''' has grown tremendously since [[New York Accords|independence]].
==Migration history== As recently as 1998, [[China Radio International]] reported there to be only fifty Chinese people doing business in Namibia, but by 2005 that had grown to more than a thousand.<ref name="ChinaCity">{{citation|periodical=China Radio International|date=2005-01-28|accessdate=2011-10-08|title=纳米比亚有座中国城 {{bracket|Namibia has a Chinatown}} |url=http://gb.cri.cn/2201/2005/01/28/381@436948.htm|author=王蕾}}</ref> A 2009 U.S. embassy estimate released by [[WikiLeaks]] in the [[United States diplomatic cables leak]] states there are three or four thousand.<ref>{{citation|url=https://wikileaks.org/cable/2009/04/09WINDHOEK118.htm|title=Update on Chinese activities in Namibia|publisher=WikiLeaks.org |date=2009-04-09|accessdate=2012-07-05}}</ref> Opposition politicians such as [[Jurie Viljoen]] of [[Monitor Action Group]] have made accusations that uncontrolled issuance of work permits has led to an influx of as many as 40,000 Chinese labourers,<ref>{{harvnb|Alden|Large|Soares de Oliveira|2008|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=k9JT3qRqxzYC&pg=PA24 240]}}</ref> a figure confirmed by Malia Politzer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.migrationinformation.org/Feature/display.cfm?id=690 |title=China and Africa: Stronger Economic Ties Mean More Migration |author=Malia Politzer |publisher=Migration Information Source |date=August 2008 |accessdate=16 September 2017}}</ref>
==Trade== In the 2000s, trade between [[China]] and [[Namibia]] grew, rising from in $75 million in 2003 to $600 million in 2009.<ref name="trade">{{citation|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201010041203.html|periodical=[[New Era (Namibia)|New Era]]|date=2010-10-04|accessdate=2011-10-08|title=Trade with China Grows|first=Chrispin|last=Inambao}}</ref> China City, a wholesale and retail centre located in an industrial area of northern Windhoek about 20 minutes from downtown, was opened in 1998 by Li Chengyuan (李澄原), a businessman from [[Taiwan]]; by 2005, merchants there were importing about 1,000 [[shipping container|container]]s of goods per year from China.<ref name="ChinaCity"/>
Many Chinese migrants establish small retail businesses particularly in clothing and jewelry.<ref name="Xoagub">{{citation|title=Namibia: Chinese 'Invasion' Gets Mixed Reaction|first=Francis|last=Xoagub|date=2011-02-17|periodical=New Era|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201102170599.html|accessdate=2011-10-08}}</ref> The arrival of Chinese traders has drawn complaints from local traders about competition and concern about quality and safety. However, some Namibians welcomed the addition of Chinese in the retail sector citing the benefit of employment creation and lower costs of goods.
[[Oshikango]], on [[:Category:Angola–Namibia border|the border]] with [[Angola]] has become a popular destination for Chinese traders hoping to take advantage of expanding cross-border trade. By 2004, the town had 22 Chinese-owned shops, expanding to 75 by 2006.<ref>{{harvnb|Alden|Large|Soares de Oliveira|2008|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=k9JT3qRqxzYC&pg=PA246 246]}}</ref> From shoes and textiles, these shops have expanded their product offerings to include furniture, home electronics, motorcycles, [[artificial flower]]s, and various other types of goods. Shop owners import their goods through the ports at [[Walvis Bay]] or [[Durban]] in [[South Africa]], and bring them in by [[rail transport in Namibia|rail]] for storage in [[bonded warehouse]]s, where they are then sold on to Angolan traders for export to Angola in small quantities, thus avoiding customs duties.<ref>{{harvnb|Alden|Large|Soares de Oliveira|2008|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=k9JT3qRqxzYC&pg=PA247 247]}}</ref> In some cases, Chinese businesspeople have set up factories in Oshikango. However these do not produce genuinely competitive goods; their main function is to get work permits for Chinese expatriates who can then work as shop assistants in import/export businesses.<ref>{{harvnb|Alden|Large|Soares de Oliveira|2008|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=k9JT3qRqxzYC&pg=PA249 249]}}</ref>
==Integration and community== There are a few Chinese restaurants (three in Windhoek) and grocery stores in the country. The restaurants are popular among local Namibians.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.newera.com.na/article.php?articleid=40599&title=Namibians%20take%20to%20Chinese%20food|title=Namibians take to Chinese food|first=Namene|last=Helmich|date=2011-09-12|accessdate=2011-10-08|periodical=New Era}}</ref>
The embassy's [[Chinese New Year]] celebration in 2010 reportedly attracted more than 1,000 Chinese guests, including migrants, international students, and representatives of Chinese multinationals stationed in the country, as well as about 100 local people.<ref>{{citation|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/overseas/2010-02/10/content_12964164.htm|date=2010-02-10|accessdate=2011-10-08|title=纳米比亚华侨华人举行春节庆祝活动 {{bracket|Overseas Chinese in Namibia hold New Year celebration activities}}|periodical=Xinhua News}}</ref>
