The '''Udeep tribe''' of [[India]] represent about 300 families living in northern India. Based solely in the [[Himachal Pradesh]] of northern India, the Udeep(s) live in two different towns each controlled by a separate clan.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://himachaltourism.gov.in/HimachalIT/Page/History.aspx |title= History of Himachal Pradesh|publisher= Himachal Tourism |accessdate=29 June 2013}}</ref> The town of Junkow is the home to the Kulkarni clan while the Chhattispur clan manages the town of Aokini. The Udeep represent some of the last vestiges of [[Jainism]] remaining in that region of India and its essence is concern for the welfare of every being in the universe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/jainism/ataglance/glance.shtml|title= Religions: Jainism at a glance|publisher=BBC|accessdate=29 June 2013}}</ref>
== History == A people of [[Dravidian people|Dravidian]] descent, when they emigrated out southern India aways from the rest of the Dravidians is unclear but the migration appears to have happened in the mid 13th century after they sided with the invading [[Mongols]] and were driven out of the Southern Peninsula.
